Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989 there were only five authorized state travel offices in then ČSSR: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
The travel offices then sold only travels to the socialist eastern block countries, in the west only elected ones.
Thus, Czech tourists traveled to the East Sea (in the German Democratic Republic - the DDR), to the Soviet Union (Sotish on the Crimean Peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when it was also allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a prowestal course and therefore the journeys to Yugoslavia were severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that it was not even allowed for citizens of the East Block (also the Czechoslovakia) to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the ČSSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travels were not possible.
Even then, the travel offices also offered travel to the west, but then they had to buy huge serpents or also stay in the bed before the travel office, or at least have "good friends" in the travel office.
Even so, it had not been done for a long time.
The so-called devisor - the condition for a journey to the West - was only given to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel.
The Czechoslovakia currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it would have been impossible to drive the necessary funds (western currency) for a journey into the West.
So most of the Czechs spent their holidays in the countryside, not a wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and dates - a habit that persists until today.
The contemporary revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on the foot.
While a vacation in the DDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things until 1989, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their foreign holidays in countries around the world.
A huge paradox, which you are no longer aware of today, is the fact that you could not travel to the most popular country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989, because it was part of the Yugoslav Republic of then.
Just from the beginning of the 1990s of the past century, the devising obligation was lifted into the neighbouring western European countries, resulting in a huge wave of short visits especially to Vienna in Austria and Germany.
The Czechoslovakians couldn't get enough from their journeys to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there at least a few days.
Thus, during traveling to Paris in the tent in the park, the Czech holidayers slept in the park, because who had already had the money for accommodation in the hotel or in a pension at that time.
A typical feature of foreign trips from Czech was then a full-packed bag room with conserves, beer and permanent worst, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades our tourists could finally buy the western currency freely.
Our level of life and then the average wages increased, which started in 1997 in another important moment.
Thanks to the increased demands for travel, travel offices began regularly to prepare travels by charter flights after 1997, making flights acceptable thanks to the possibility of negotiating discounts compared to the past.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, had already devisible payment traffic with all the highly developed countries of the world, making traveling even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of the "post-allocation" travel was found in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights with Czech passengers have been flying every year in far-distance sunny countries; this year they fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
To the 100 Tsd. Czechs travel every year in exotic countries!
Another significant moment in the Epoch, which marked our "post-revolutionary" development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US lifted the visa obligation for Czech tourists, which definitely ranked our country among the highly developed countries of the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half their vacation abroad (50.3%) for the first time in their history, they spent more than 15 Tsd. CZK per head for a single vacation, including the costs at the vacation site.
