Rafael Herrera, researchers at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico of UNAM developed modified asphalts with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs that come from the road coating would not be necessary to repair nearly 200 000 sludges when the raining time at Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (City area of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera Najera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at UNAM University, warned and assured that if the excavation and maintenance of the asphalt coating is appropriate, the number of sludges will be significantly reduced or even completely avoided.
In his lecture "Slowers from a technical point of view", which he held to chemistry at the time of the International Year, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, which, however, has a greater mechanical resistance both at high and at low temperatures.
Mrera Najera said that this type of modified asphalts in areas with extremely hot climate, such as in some cities in the north of the country, should be used to improve the behaviour of the road coating and thus avoid the appearance of sludges.
He explained that the asphalt - the most severe part of the oil - is a carbon hydrogen compound, of which some have a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthen. Together, they give to the road coating its characteristic telastic behavior.
The denelastic behaviour of the asphalt means that at high temperatures of nearly 180°C it behaves like a liquid, at 120°C it is very thin and almost fixed at 50°C, while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistability of asphalt on the roads is not equal, but changes on one day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," the chemical engineer concluded.
The researcher of the FQ noted that the streets of Mexico City had a majority of a flexible road coating composed of six materials layers, of which the last three asphalts included.
Between the top layers lies a layer of asphalt, which consists of small, asphalt bathed and then fixed stones.
Each single stone of this clothing layer was bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles are moved on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road coating.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," said the chemistry engineer.
"About the cutting layer," he explained, "was a last layer designed, the so-called coating layer made of small stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tyres, they need a greater mechanical force than the trailing layer and it must produce vibration.
The most powers received and distributed by this road coating also require an appropriate thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
